;************************INCLUDE FILE*****************************
;(do not assemble stand-alone.  )
				.TF     DATA.SPR.SURFACE.BIN,BIN
				.OR		$A900			**Always put before .TF directive and never use again in program
				.EB		OFF
				
;=====================DATA FILE DOCUMENTATION====================================
;
;==Overview==
;This data files stores the map objects data for the location described in the .TF filename above.
;
;==Order of Arrays==
;The order of the data arrays is critial. 
;They must be in the following order:
;
;DATA.SPR.SURFACE.MOB
;DATA.SPR.SURFACE.GENERAL
;DATA.SPR.SURFACE.NPC
;NPC.L1.F1.SCHEDULE
;NPC.L1.F1.SCHEDULE2
;
;Or, instead of NPC scheduled arrays, FILLER.DATA.SPR.SURFACE if on any map other than a building
;
;==Size of Data==
;PRODOS.IO can only handle writes that are for an even number of pages (i.. 2,4,6,8,A)
;If an odd number of pages is used, the driver will round up the to the nearest even page and clobber data in the file. 
;As an alternative to this file containing an even number of pages of data, filler can also be used, in which case the driver's rounding of the write
;size has no impact on real data.  
;=================================================================================
					

					
	;****ORDER OF ARRAYS IS CRITICAL (see data file documentation section above)

	;****THIS FILE MUST BE AN EVEN # OF PAGES OR END WITH FILLER (see ==Size of Data== in the data file documentation section above)
	


;NPC.SCHEDULE
	
		;**This .NO fills the 3 pages allocated for the NPC.SCHEDULE arrray. This is needed to
		;ensure the subsquent arrays end up in the correct memory locations
	.NO $AC00
		;*OPT** Speed. Disk storage. The above .NO could be eliminates, possibly savings some disk space (consider the 
		;2 page write minimum, 2 block file size mimimum on disk, etc) if .SAVE.SPR.DATA were to open the file and seek 
		;$300 bytes ahead before doing the write. The result would be that the write could start with the mob array,
		;skipping the scheudle data, which never changes. This would reduce the I/O time to exit a town back to the 
		;surface. If this is done, the write size would get reduced, I think back to 4 pages (that is what is was before 
		;I moved the map object arrays around, which is when this .NO got added. If this optimization is done, it is
		;also a good time to add open+seek support to the ProRWTS2 wrapper. That way the Open+seek can be done with 
		;1 call to the wrapper, saving memory in .SAVE.SPR.DATA and any other routine in the future that would benifit
		;from an open+seek call. 
	
